        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-05-06T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-05-06T02:00:00-05:00" n="346" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d346">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/5–649: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister-Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Clark</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Canton</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-05-06T15:00:00+08:00">May 6, 1949—3 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received May 6—2:10 p. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Cantel 323. Returned from Kweilin where he went heading C–C delegation seeking
                    return Canton Li Tsung-jen, Marshal Yen Hsi-shan tells us Li continues refuse
                    come Canton until assured free hand running government. In addition to control
                    over finances and economic planning, Yen says military strategy is one of main
                    points of conflict between Li and Generalissimo, claiming Generalissimo wants
                    defend coast while Li favors withdrawal into interior.</p>
                <p>Repeated Nanking 249, Shanghai 205.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Clark</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
